hello,

I'm trying to get working a pixel shader that works perfectly in windows phone, windows (directx), windows 8 and android, but on iOS seems to be some kind of mistake when I pass a texture as parameter on ios, does not throw any error at runtime, simply it don't get the texture. I also tried with the last sources of monogame from github.

my pixel shader:

``` HLSL
sampler TextureSampler : register(s0);

texture MaskTexture;
sampler mask = sampler_state
{
    Texture = <MaskTexture>;
};

float4 PixelShaderFunction(float4 pos : SV_POSITION, float4 color1 : COLOR0, float2 coords : TEXCOORD0) : SV_TARGET0
{
    float4 color = tex2D(TextureSampler, coords);
    return color * tex2D(mask, coords);
}

technique Technique1
{
    pass Pass1
    {
#if SM4
    PixelShader = compile ps_4_0_level_9_1 PixelShaderFunction();
#elif SM3
    PixelShader = compile ps_3_0 PixelShaderFunction();
#else
    PixelShader = compile ps_2_0 PixelShaderFunction();
#endif
    }
}
```

on my Draw method...

``` C#
            spriteBatch.Begin(SpriteSortMode.Immediate, BlendState.AlphaBlend);
            Efecto.Parameters["MaskTexture"].SetValue(Mascara); // This parameter does not work on ios, it gives a black box
            Efecto.CurrentTechnique.Passes[0].Apply();
            spriteBatch.Draw(Avatar, Vector2.Zero, Color.White);
            spriteBatch.End();
```

The result should be:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5202166/11962898/878bc284-a8e3-11e5-9093-78906d64bb1c.png)

but I only get a black box... I also tried to directly return the texture color on the shader without parameter to be sure that the shader is applied and it works, the problem seems to be the texture as parameter.

As I said, it works on Android, Windows Phone and Windows using DX monogame, but does not on IOS (tried on emulator, iPhone 5 and iPhone 6)

Thanks

Hello,

I've noticed a discrepancy between Windows and DesktopGL platforms regarding `GraphicsDevice.Viewport` initialization.

On Windows, the `GraphicsDevice.Viewport` is initialized by `GraphicsDeviceManager.ApplyChanges()`, but on DesktopGL, `GraphicsDeviceManager.ApplyChanges()` doesn't initialize it.
It seems to be only initialized upon `Game.Initialize()` (base class).

Would it be ok to do so in `OpenTKGamePlatform.ResetWindowBounds()`?

```
            if (device != null)
            {
                PresentationParameters parms = device.PresentationParameters;
                parms.BackBufferHeight = (int)bounds.Height;
                parms.BackBufferWidth = (int)bounds.Width;

                var viewport = new Viewport(0, 0,
                            parms.BackBufferWidth,
                            parms.BackBufferHeight);

                device.Viewport = viewport;
            }
```

If that's ok, I'll submit a PR.

In Protogame, I have a custom asset management system which works differently to the way MonoGame models it's content.  However, I still use the internal content pipeline to process assets from their raw formats to the platform-specific binary data.

The issue I'm having is that the content importers accept a filename instead of a stream or byte array.  This means that I'm either forced to copy the content importer implementation into Protogame, or write out the binary data to a temporary file on disk before importing it.

I'm proposing that we add the following signature to `ContentImporter<T>`:

```
public virtual T Import(Stream input, ContentImporterContext context)
{
  // default implementation that writes to a temporary file
}
```

Then for all the MonoGame implementations we can move most of the code into an `override` of this method, and change the `Import` that uses a filename to read the file binary data before calling the stream-based version.  By doing it this way, we ensure that we don't break anyone who is currently deriving from `ContentImporter` (because the method we're adding is virtual, and provides an implementation that is backwards-compatible, if less ideal).
